                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Pottsville</placeName>
                                        <date>October 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1851</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Rev. &amp; Dear Sir,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Although an entire stranger to you,<lb/> I hope
                                        you will excuse the liberty I now take in addres<lb/>sing
                                        you.   You are known to me by reputation, as<lb/> one
                                        thoroughly learned in ancient as well as modern<lb/> Hebrew
                                        lore; and as possessing a <add>?</add> of information<lb/>
                                        on general matters connected with the history of<lb/> your
                                        race, rarely to be found. And I hope that my<lb/> earnest
                                        desire to attain the knowledge of the truth<lb/> will be a
                                        sufficient apology for my addressing you this<lb/> letter.
                                          My object in writing you, is, to ob<lb/>tain for my own
                                        individual benefit, some information<lb/> in regard to the
                                        practice of the Israelites in the cele-<lb/>bration of the
                                                  <date>Passover</date> about the time of the birth of<lb/>
                                        <persName>Christ</persName>. And that you may readily
                                        apprehend what<lb/> I want to be at, I will reduce it to the
                                        form of a<lb/> question. What was the subject matter of
                                        praise<lb/> at the conclusion of the <date>Passover</date>
                                        service? Was it<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">the Hallel</hi> embracing Psalms
                                        113-117? or was it a<lb/> Hymn composed in honor of the
                                        expected Messiah?</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The church with which I am connected uses<lb/>
                                        exclusively the Psalms of David, rendered into
                                                  rueter<add>?</add>,<lb/> in the worship of God:
                                        and her reason for so doing, is<lb/> the example of the
                                        founder of the Christian religion.</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>who in conformity with Jewish custom, celebrated his<lb/> last
                                                  <date>Passover</date> by using the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Hallel</hi> referred to,
                                        intimating<lb/> thereby, that he would have his disciples
                                        use the Psalms<lb/> of David exclusively in the worship of
                                        God to the end<lb/> of the world. (This is not the only
                                        reason for our prac-<lb/>tice, but it is one of the
                                        principal ones.)</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have recently heard it objected, that
                                                  <persName>Christ</persName> did not<lb/> use the
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Hallel</hi> in the instance
                                        referred to, for it was<lb/> not the custom of the Jews to
                                        use it on such an occas<lb/>sion, but to sing a Hymn in
                                        honor of the expected<lb/> Messiah—the same Hymn now
                                        contained in the<lb/> “<hi rend="underline">Hagada al
                                                  Passah</hi>,” and still sung at the
                                        conclusion<lb/> of that service.   If such a Hymn was
                                        used<lb/> at the time referred to, and is now contained in
                                        the<lb/> “Hagada” and is still used: be so kind as to give
                                        me<lb/> its history—when it first began to be used, and
                                        by<lb/> whom composed: and also where I can obtain a
                                        copy<lb/> of the “Hagada” in Hebrew and English.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I write this in all candor and honesty, and
                                        sincerely desire<lb/> that you will favor me with an answer
                                        and throw some<lb/> light on a subject, in regard to which I
                                        have seen nothing<lb/> yet satisfactory.   </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">With great regard</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Yours very sincerely</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <persName role="author">D. T. Carnahan</persName>
                              </p>
                    </body>
